<br>
My system ain't powerful enough yet to handle much of Camelot, so haven't been able to experience much of the game. What I have seen however is enough to warrant me throwing out EQ for a while, though. EQ has become so... awful lately, for me. Same stuff over and over, only thing to look forward to is killing a mess of polygons to get an item with some numbers on it. Camelot has that in it certainly, but RvR makes things much more interesting. RvR may not be the most balanced thing in the world, but it's at least something different to participate in when you don't want to fight the same old dragon for the 50th time to get those 40ac gauntlets.<br>
<br>
Don't see the logic of those that complain about Camelot's graphics <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  It's all so much prettier in Camelot heh. I'm happy enough trading in the various parts of eyecandy in EQ for rolling hills in Camelot. The architecture in the cities is certainly nice.<br>
<br>
I have doubts about the in game CS. Seems it'd be difficult to handle everything with a lower amount of CSR in the game. The player based advisor system may turn out to be pretty good.<br>
<br>
Unless Luclin can fully put the fun back into the game with its supposed more single or 2 or 3 group friendly zones, which I doubt, I'll retire my EQ characters. Haven't played EQ in a month anyways. Brad's leaving VI doesn't add much confidence for the future of EQ. Camelot's almost flawless launch, stable servers, more complicated combat, and already indications of an expansion pack soon puts much confidence into the future of Camelot, though.<br>
